This change is needed for building on Debian11+ (bullseye) (and ubuntu2104+ hirsute) as the dh-systemd transitional package has been removed in these releases. (the functionality is folded into debhelper 10 and above).

https://packages.debian.org/buster/dh-systemd
https://packages.ubuntu.com/groovy/dh-systemd

However it's still compatible with older Debian/Ubuntu releases that contain at least debhelper 10 (stretch and bionic)

An IPv6 router in general should implement the weak host model.
I.e be capable of sending and accepting packets with source address / destination address from another interface than the output/input interface.

Patch Set 1:

Leaving as comments two thing that I will otherwise forget:
1) maybe use ip.adj_index[VLIB_RX] to figure out what local adjacency received the packet
2) we should consider the option of updating sw_if_index[VLIB_RX] when a packet hits ipX_local

Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Leaving as comments two thing that I will otherwise forget:
> 1) maybe use ip.adj_index[VLIB_RX] to figure out what local adjacency received the packet
> 2) we should consider the option of updating sw_if_index[VLIB_RX] when a packet hits ipX_local

Thanks for the comments ! Adding a couple thoughts for the sake of the discussion 😊
3) ip.adj_index[VLIB_RX] might collide with tcp.connection_index which might lead to the same issue
4) updating sw_if_index[VLIB_RX] in the ipX_local node will change the punt redirect node's behavior. No clear opinion on whether someone would be relying on the prior behavior. But breaking changes are tricky...
5) So alternatively we can also make ip.fib_index & tcp.connection_index match positions so that the tcp vars don't override fib_index. I updated [0] to reflect this

[0] https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/33313

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 1: -Code-Review
> 
> > Patch Set 1:
> > 
> > Leaving as comments two thing that I will otherwise forget:
> > 1) maybe use ip.adj_index[VLIB_RX] to figure out what local adjacency received the packet
> > 2) we should consider the option of updating sw_if_index[VLIB_RX] when a packet hits ipX_local
> 
> Thanks for the comments ! Adding a couple thoughts for the sake of the discussion 😊
> 3) ip.adj_index[VLIB_RX] might collide with tcp.connection_index which might lead to the same issue
> 4) updating sw_if_index[VLIB_RX] in the ipX_local node will change the punt redirect node's behavior. No clear opinion on whether someone would be relying on the prior behavior. But breaking changes are tricky...
> 5) So alternatively we can also make ip.fib_index & tcp.connection_index match positions so that the tcp vars don't override fib_index. I updated [0] to reflect this
> 
> [0] https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/33313

Regarding 4), I think we need to have that conversation independent of how we move forward with this. As it stands, ip local feature arc is useless after routing between local interfaces and probably we have several pieces of code that wrongly assume packets are consumed/received by the ingress interface not by the one with the dst ip. 

If that is eventually fixed, we can completely avoid the bihash lookup for punt and the code should be less fragile. Yes, we may fix tcp, but anything else that ends up in punt might have garbage in ip.fib_index. 

With regard to the purpose of the patch, haven't yet read it in detail, interfaces are associated to only one fib_index, so what does this add functionally? That is, sw_if_index 1 in fib_index 1, shouldn't be looked up as sw_if_index 1 in fib_index 2.

Patch Set 2:

Hi Mohammed,
do these changes look OK to you?
/neale

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Hi everyone, sorry for the late review.
It doesn't look ok to me actually, because I've specifically put the setup interrupt here for a reason :)
There is a dependency in certain DPDK drivers (typically i40e) that requires the device be started (with rte_eth_dev_start) before trying to enable interrupts (because the interrupt vector is not ready yet). Take a look at (in the DPDK code) i40e_dev_rx_queue_intr_enable and i40e_dev_start. In this case the intr_vec data structure is initialised in the dev_start function, and used by the intr_enable function later.
Best regards,
Mohammed

Patch Set 2:

Thanks for the review and pointing out the issue - I'll look solving the higher-level issue with a different approach.
